 threads of his often paradoxical and counterintuitive ideas from the tangled thickets of his writings, explaining their significance, their interconnections, and the astonishing appeal they so rapidly developed. Yet Rex also sets these ideas firmly in the context of Luther’s personal life, the cultural landscape that shaped him, and the traditions of medieval Catholic thought from which his ideas burst forth.Lucidly argued and elegantly written, The Making of Martin Luther is a splendid work of intellectual history that renders Luther’s earthshaking yet sometimes challenging ideas accessible to a new generation of readers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aReformation. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Protestant.2bisacsh  aAdelmann.  aAllusion.  aAnabaptists.  aAntichrist.  aAntinomianism.  aAugustine of Hippo.  aBible.  aBiblical literalism.  aBlasphemy.  aCalvinism.  aCanon law.  aCatholic Church.  aCatholic theology.  aCatholicism.  aCensure.  aCertainty.  aChrist.  aChristendom.  aChristian theology.  aChristian.  aChristianity.  aClergy.  aConcupiscence.  aConscience.  aCouncil of Constance.  aDisputation.  aDivine grace.  aDoctrine.  aDominican Order.  aEcclesiology.  aEcumenical council.  aEpistle.  aErfurt.  aExcommunication.  aExegesis.  aExsurge Domine.  aFigure of speech.  aFranciscans.  aFriar.  aGod.  aHeresy.  aHussites.  aIndulgence.  aInvisible church.  aJan Hus.  aJohann von Staupitz.  aJohn Chrysostom.  aJustification (theology).  aLaw and Gospel.  aLecture.  aLutheranism.  aMartin Bucer.  aMartin Luther.  aMartyr.  aMonasticism.  aNew Testament.  aNinety-five Theses.  aOld Testament.  aOrthodoxy.  aPamphlet.  aPapal bull.  aPapal primacy.  aPapist.  aPaul the Apostle.  aPelagi